"Picked up a six pack of this stuff yesterday for 9 bucks (!) Pours a nice amber color, a bit darker than your typical amber, but it looks really nice. Pretty good head. Very clear. Smell is a little more subtle than I was expecting, but it's a nice melony, slightly skunky smell that you can get with citra in the mix. Not what you typically find in an amber, but it's interesting and it works. Taste was very good. Again, I'm a little partial to that classic cascadey taste in an amber, but this is a nice change up. Mouthfeel is excellent! It's got a nice smooth, slipperiness to it, that I really like. All told, a unique and tasty American amber ale that you should try if you dig that style of beer. Good stuff!"
""
"This beer looks amazing. It has this incredibly vibrant caramel-ruby hue with a nice lacing. There’s a fantastic aroma to it—I can tell it’s fresh because the hops are just vibrant. I pick up a bit of pine and grapefruit that’s overshadowed by a sticky, dank, resiny note and held together with a caramelly-malty backbone. The aroma profile carries over to the flavor, with a smooth and surprisingly mellow bitterness lending some complexity to the lingering sticky-green-malty taste. It's good stuff. a little malty, kinda catty, slightly dank... it’s solid and scratches that itch, and for the price it’s a steal. One I will definitely seek out again."
"Outweighing the factors, this is not as drinkable as I'd like it to be. I'd sooner have Celebration than have another bottle of this anytime soon. The hoppy profile gets lost in between the dry, gritty malty character, in spite of the fact that this shows flavors I haven't quite seen before in a hoppy amber ale. Not a bad choice from the Fall, but a little too heavy and lacking of refreshing characteristics I enjoy in the style. Not a misstep by SN, but definitely below what they're capable of doing."
